  "prompt": "Why does water spread grease and oil fires?",
  "response": "Water spreads grease and oil fires because of a few key reasons related to the properties of both water and these types of flammable liquids:\n\n*   **Immiscibility:** Water and grease/oil don't mix (they are immiscible). When you pour water onto a grease or oil fire, the water sinks to the bottom because it's denser.\n\n*   **Vaporization and Splattering:** The water quickly boils and vaporizes when it comes into contact with the extremely hot grease or oil. This rapid vaporization causes the hot grease/oil to splatter violently.\n\n*   **Increased Surface Area:** The splattering spreads the burning grease or oil over a much wider area.  This creates more small fires and makes the overall fire larger and more difficult to control.\n\n*   **Grease/Oil Floats:** Because water is denser than grease or oil, the burning grease/oil floats on top of the water. As the water flows, it carries the burning grease/oil with it, spreading the fire to new areas.\n\nIn essence, instead of smothering the fire, water disperses the burning fuel, making the situation worse.\n\n**Important Note:** This is why you should NEVER use water on a grease or oil fire. Instead, you should smother the fire with a lid, baking soda, or a Class B fire extinguisher.",
